title: NCHWc Upsample/Mul optimizations
body:
**Description**: Extend the NCHWc layout optimizer to handle Resize(mode=nearest) and Mul.

**Motivation and Context**
Add support for trivial Upsample and Resize ops using nearest mode upsampling with integer scaling in the NCHWc domain. This is meant to handle UNet and YOLOV3 models that have an UpsampleNearest(2x2) node. This avoids unnecessary tensor reordering around the upsampling.

Also reuse the existing Add/Sum support to keep tensors in NCHWc when both inputs of a Mul node are already in NCHWc format.

One internal model using Upsample and Mul went from 27ms->21ms per inference. tinyyolov3 from the model zoo went from 16ms->14ms.

I'm removing the WCOS/Win32 hacks and using the CMake cross-compilation options to target WCOS or Win32.  ----

**Description**: WCOS/Win32 linking options were error prone, because CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD_LIBRARIES was left at the default value (which includes Win32 libs). import torch

class BadBlock(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, n_inputs, n_outputs, kernel_size, dontbebad=False):
        super(BadBlock, self).__init__()
        conv = nn.Conv1d(n_inputs, n_outputs, kernel_size)
        self.conv = conv if dontbebad else weight_norm(conv) 
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()

savname_onnx = 'test_onnxrt_model.onnx'

input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
result = sess.run(None, {input_name: real_input.numpy()})
result = np.array(result)

ref_out = ref_out[0, 0, :]

title: OnnxTensor.createTensor should support Nd4j Objects
body:
Currently to create a tensor we need to reshape the image. A common way to do this in Java is to use the Nd4j Lib (http://nd4j.org/index.html). This Lib uses c libs in the background to perform the calculations which of course moves the data away from the JVM. As the function OnnxTensor.createTensor(OnnxInferencer.getEnvironment, array) does kind the same we could have a performance improvement if read Nd4j objects directly that is already in the c stack let's say so. 

As an example: 


       val ndArray = Nd4j.create(data) <--- Copies data into C stack
        val indexW = row.getAs[Int](config.widthField)
        val indexH = row.getAs[Int](config.heightField)
        val reshaped = ndArray.reshape(indexH, indexW, 3)
        val normalizationArray = Array(102.9801, 115.9465, 122.7717)
        val normNd4j = Nd4j.create(normalizationArray)
        val normalized = reshaped.sub(normNd4j)
        //This is very expensive as it copies
        val backToHeap = normalized.ravel.toDoubleVector <-- Copies data from C Stack into JVM
        val tensor = OnnxTensor.createTensor(OnnxInferencer.getEnvironment, backToHeap) <-- Copies the JVM data back to C stack but for Onnx.
 
How it could be: 



        val ndArray = Nd4j.create(data) <--- Copies data into C stack
        val indexW = row.getAs[Int](config.widthField)
        val indexH = row.getAs[Int](config.heightField)
        val reshaped = ndArray.reshape(indexH, indexW, 3)
        val normalizationArray = Array(102.9801, 115.9465, 122.7717)
        val normNd4j = Nd4j.create(normalizationArray)
        val normalized = reshaped.sub(normNd4j)
        val tensor = OnnxTensor.createTensor(OnnxInferencer.getEnvironment, normalized)  <-- No Copies to JVM

title: update C# API to optimize inference latency
body:
**Description**: This change update ONNXRuntime C# API to support more override of `InferenceSession.Run()`.

**Features**:
- Support pre-allocated outputs with determined types and dimensions.
- Support a new type `PinnedOnnxValue` to allow user to reuse the underlying native `OrtValue` for multiple times.
- Added overrides of the combination of above with no break of any existing interface.

**Motivation and Context**
- ONNXRuntime C# does not have a good inference performance with small models under a multi-thread situation. The main reason is that the current C# API always allocate buffers for outputs and create native `OrtValue` objects in `InferenceSession.Run()`. However, this can be avoid by calling C-API with a pre-allocated output list and use a pinned memory, as discussed in the design review meeting.

title: Delay-loading of onnxruntime.dll fails
body:
**Describe the bug**
Since v1.1.0 it is not possible any more to delay-load `onnxruntime.dll`. This is due to the following code lines in `onnxruntime_cxx_api.h` which are embedded in all modules using the API header: They call a function in the DLL during the static initialization of the implementing module and thus require `onnxruntime.dll` to be already loaded:
```
template <typename T>
const OrtApi& Global<T>::api_ = *OrtGetApiBase()->GetApi(ORT_API_VERSION);
```

In our application we only want to load `onnxruntime.dll` when it is really required.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.1.2
- Python version: 3.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): Visual Studio 2015

**To Reproduce**

- Create a minimalistic command line project (see code below)
- Use onnxruntime as a dynamic library (set linker _additional dependencies_ `onnxruntime.lib` and _additional library directories_)
- Add `onnxruntime.dll` under Linker | Input | Delay Loaded Dlls
- Run the executable **without** providing onnxruntime.dll and with no command line arguments.
- The program will crash at the following line in `onnxruntime_cxx_api.h` although the onnxruntime API is not used.
  `const OrtApi& Global<T>::api_ = *OrtGetApiBase()->GetApi(ORT_API_VERSION);`

```
#include "stdafx.h"
#include "onnxruntime_cxx_api.h"

int main(int argc, char** argv)
{
	if (argc > 1)
	{
		volatile const OrtApiBase* baseApi = OrtGetApiBase();
	}
    return 0;
}
```

**Expected behavior**
I would expect the executable not trying to load `onnxruntime.dll` because there are not API functions being called when `argc == 1`.

This could be achieved by implementing an explicit library initialization method which has to be called by the user of onnxruntime.

**Screenshots**
![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8805876/76295179-72ed2180-62b4-11ea-9ef6-ae4ab636b42e.png)

**Additional context**
I think pull request #2228 has broken the ability to delay-load `onnxruntime.dll` because it performs calls to the API during static initialization of each implementing module.

The pre-processor define `EXCLUDE_REFERENCE_TO_ORT_DLL` does not much improve the situation because it would only allow **one** compilation unit to include `onnxruntime_cxx_api.h`. If included by multiple compilation units, the linker will issue an error LNK4006 (_symbol already defined in object_).

title: Add support for sessions to share a global threadpool.
body:
**Description**: Add support for sessions to share a global threadpool.

**Motivation and Context**
The OCR team has a requirement to run multiple sessions (models) in a process. ORT creates an intra and inter thread pool for every session. This is clearly not efficient in this scenario. Hence, we need to design a way to have these 2 thread pools be shared between multiple sessions. 

After discussion with the OCR team, option #3 in this [design doc](https://microsoft-my.sharepoint.com/:w:/p/prs/EeFinr4HDkRBpe8T7iPlCvcBtKmVohRbAAG4BSEa4CX9qg?e=bHgOBS) seems to be the simplest. They don't have any requirement for this feature to be available in language bindings other than C/C++.

Usage will be as follows. Also see documentation under docs/C_API.md.
1. Call CreateEnvWithGlobalThreadPools()
2. Call DisablePerSessionThreads()
3. Call Run()

Also moved the logger to the Environment class as part of this change to facilitate easier passing of global threadpools to session. We wanted to do this any way.

title: QLinearConv speed up
body:
**Description**: For x86/x64 builds, change the QLinearConv op to use MLAS for the u8u8=s32 GEMM, then requantize the intermediate buffer to u8.

**Motivation and Context**
The existing implementation of QLinearConv was using gemmlowp without threading and was restricted to SSE4.1. This changes the kernel to instead use MLAS for threading and scalable instruction set. 

The requantization is changed from the gemmlowp fixed point strategy to use FP32 instructions, which is simpler on x86/x64. This makes the results not bit identical to the old version: for results near y.499xx, the gemmlowp version would round up to the next integer. The new version rounds this down instead.

For the reference quantized resnet50v1 model, times goes from 2053ms->42ms. The ConvInteger version of the model is now a little slower at 45ms. Not terribly great numbers to brag about yet.

title: Segfault when reducing a 0D Tensor
body:
**Describe the bug**
As a self-contained example, consider the following case where we attempt to reduce a 0D tensor:

```
TEST(ReductionOpTest, Reduce0DTensor) {
  OpTester test("ReduceMin");
  test.AddInput<float>("data", {}, {2});
  test.AddOutput<float>("reduced", {}, {2});
  test.Run();
}
```

This seems to result in a segmentation fault at `PrepareForReduce` in `reduction_ops.cc`. Within that function, because `ndim == 0` and `axes.size() == 0`, when the following conditions are evaluated 

```
  if (axes.size() <= ndim &&
      axes.front() == static_cast<int64_t>(ndim - axes.size()) &&
      axes.back() == static_cast<int64_t>(ndim) - 1) {
    need_copy = false;
  }
```

we will attempt to dereference `axes.front()` which will segfault. Assuming this is the issue, it should be straightforward to add a check for the case for `ndim == 0` and skip reduction entirely.

**Urgency**
Severity is probably P2. We ran into this issue trying to perform post-training quantization on a BERT network; there is no a hard deadline though.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 16.04 
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Exists in both binary installed from pypi and from source
- ONNX Runtime version: Pypi version 1.20, source built from HEAD
- Python version: 3.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): 9.2.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: N/A
- GPU model and memory: N/A

**To Reproduce**
The aforementioned test case should demonstrate the issue. A segfault is observed at the line where `axes.front()` is dereferenced.

**Expected behavior**
Reduction on a 0D tensor should just return that single scalar untouched when applicable.
